Backend MVP design





Auth and user management





Implement email + password registration and login with JWT-based auth in [backend/app/api/routes_users.py](backend/app/api/routes_users.py).



Use [backend/app/core/security.py](backend/app/core/security.py) for password hashing, JWT creation/verification, and auth dependencies (get_current_user).



Define User model in [backend/app/models/user.py](backend/app/models/user.py) with fields for id, email, hashed password, profile metadata, resume path, and preferences JSON.



Provide endpoints for registration, login, token refresh, and GET /users/me to fetch the current profile.



Resume ingestion and preferences





Add POST /users/me/resume in [backend/app/api/routes_users.py](backend/app/api/routes_users.py) to upload a resume file (multipart).



Store the raw file path (local disk for dev) and hand off to [backend/app/services/resume_parser.py](backend/app/services/resume_parser.py) for parsing skills, titles, experience, and inferred preferences.



Add PUT /users/me/preferences and GET /users/me/preferences endpoints to manage target roles, locations, salary range, job types, and aggressiveness level.



Persist structured preferences and parsed resume features on the User model, keeping raw file location separate from extracted data.



Job and application models





Implement Job model in [backend/app/models/job.py](backend/app/models/job.py) with title, company, location, description, salary info, source, external ID, URL, and timestamps.



Implement JobApplication model in [backend/app/models/application.py](backend/app/models/application.py) with foreign keys to user and job, status (queued, submitted, rejected, interview, etc.), provider metadata, and timestamps.



Expose basic read endpoints in [backend/app/api/routes_jobs.py](backend/app/api/routes_jobs.py) for listing a user’s jobs, matches, and applications.



Matching service





Implement [backend/app/services/matching.py](backend/app/services/matching.py) with a function score_job_for_user(user_profile, job) that calls the LLM.



Define an internal UserProfile representation combining resume features and explicit preferences.



Return a numeric relevance score and short explanation string for each job; store these in the DB for later inspection.



Background processing and scheduling





Choose Redis + RQ or Celery in [backend/app/workers/queue.py](backend/app/workers/queue.py) and provide helpers to enqueue tasks.



Implement [backend/app/workers/tasks.py](backend/app/workers/tasks.py) with:





discover_jobs_for_user(user_id): call each enabled provider’s search_jobs, create/update Job records, and enqueue scoring.



auto_apply_for_user(user_id): for jobs above a user-specific threshold and satisfying constraints, call provider apply_to_job and create JobApplication records.



Use [backend/app/services/scheduler.py](backend/app/services/scheduler.py) with APScheduler or external cron to periodically run discover_jobs_for_user for active users.



Provider integrations





Define JobProvider interface in [backend/app/integrations/base.py](backend/app/integrations/base.py):





search_jobs(user_profile) -> list[Job].



can_auto_apply() -> bool.



apply_to_job(job, user_profile) -> ApplicationResult.



Implement initial stub classes for LinkedIn, Unstop, and Indeed in their respective modules with:





Realistic search_jobs using public search pages or APIs where feasible.



Placeholder apply_to_job that records intent but does not submit forms yet.



Add [backend/app/api/routes_integrations.py](backend/app/api/routes_integrations.py) endpoints to report provider connection status and, later, handle cookie/session/token setup.



Automation layer





Add an automation/ submodule (or extend workers/) to run Playwright or Selenium flows.



For each provider, plan flows to:





Log in using stored session/cookies or token-based auth where possible.



Build search filters from user preferences and run searches.



Auto-fill application forms using user profile and resume.



Implement rate limiting, randomized delays, and robust logging/error handling to reduce bot-detection risk.

Frontend MVP design





Authentication and layout





Implement login and registration in [frontend/pages/index.tsx](frontend/pages/index.tsx) using FastAPI auth endpoints.



Create a protected [frontend/pages/dashboard.tsx](frontend/pages/dashboard.tsx) that requires a valid JWT (stored in local storage for MVP) and redirects unauthenticated users.



Build a shared layout with a sidebar (Dashboard, Job Matches, Applications, Settings) and top-level error/toast messaging.



Key screens and components





Dashboard (dashboard.tsx)





Summary cards for jobs discovered in the last 24 hours, jobs auto-applied, and pending responses.



Table or list of recent applications with status and provider.



Resume and preferences (settings/preferences.tsx)





ResumeUploader for uploading resumes and showing parsed summary and skills.



PreferencesForm for target roles, locations, salary range, job types, and aggressiveness slider controlling match threshold.



Connections (settings/connections.tsx)





ProviderConnectionCard for LinkedIn, Unstop, and Indeed, showing connection status and linking to instructions on providing cookies/tokens or future OAuth.



Job matches and logs





JobMatchList to display potential matches with LLM score, explanation, and auto-apply toggle (per user or per provider).



ApplicationLog to display a timeline or table of auto-applied jobs and their evolving status.



API client and types





Define shared types in [frontend/lib/types.ts](frontend/lib/types.ts) that mirror FastAPI Pydantic schemas: User, UserProfile, Job, JobMatch, Application, ProviderStatus, etc.



Implement [frontend/lib/api.ts](frontend/lib/api.ts) with helper functions for:





Auth: register, login, refresh token, get current user.



User data: get/update preferences, upload resume.



Jobs: get matches, get applications.



Integrations: get provider statuses, update connection info when supported.

Infra, security, and quality





Security stance





Avoid storing raw passwords for third-party job sites; prefer API keys, OAuth, or browser-based session cookies.



When credentials or cookies must be stored, encrypt at rest (e.g., using a KMS or application-level encryption) and restrict access by user.



Store JWT secrets and provider keys in environment variables loaded via [backend/app/core/config.py](backend/app/core/config.py) and infrastructure/env.example.



Local development





infrastructure/docker-compose.yml spins up Postgres, Redis, the FastAPI backend (including workers), and the Next.js frontend.



Document setup in README.md: prerequisites (Docker, Python, Node), environment variable configuration, and docker-compose up workflow.



Testing and linting





Backend





Configure pytest and add tests for models, auth endpoints, matching, and at least one provider stub.



Use ruff and black for linting/formatting, configured in backend/pyproject.toml or equivalent.



Frontend





Configure Jest and React Testing Library for testing core components (ResumeUploader, PreferencesForm, JobMatchList).



Use eslint and prettier with TypeScript support.



CI





.github/workflows/ci.yml to install backend and frontend dependencies, run tests, and run linters on pushes and pull requests.

Milestones





Milestone 1: Repo and scaffolding





Create base directory structure (backend/, frontend/, infrastructure/, .github/).



Scaffold FastAPI app with a health-check route and Next.js app with a starter page.



Add initial README.md with high-level description and setup instructions.



Milestone 2: Users, resume, and preferences





Implement auth, resume upload endpoint, and preference storage in the backend.



Build frontend forms for login/register, resume upload, and preferences.



Wire frontend to backend APIs for this flow end to end.



Milestone 3: Job model, matching, and fake provider





Implement Job and JobApplication models and migrations.



Implement matching.py with LLM-based scoring and a FakeProvider returning hardcoded jobs for testing.



Surface fake provider matches and applications in the dashboard UI.



Milestone 4: Real provider search integration





Implement read-only search integrations for LinkedIn, Unstop, and Indeed.



Display real matches from these providers in JobMatchList with scores.



Milestone 5: Controlled auto-apply





Implement at least one real automation flow (e.g., LinkedIn) behind a feature flag.



Add per-user toggles for auto-apply vs review-first and enforce global/per-provider rate limits.



Milestone 6: Hardening and observability





Improve logging, error handling, and tracing for backend, workers, and automation flows.



Tighten auth, secure storage of sensitive data, and document operational playbooks.



Ensure CI is stable and add basic monitoring hooks where feasible.



